Humanitarian crisis with high abortion rate
The Federal Republic of Somalia’s experience with terrorism led to increased suicide bombings and bombings in public spaces. The bombings in 2008 led to over 850 deaths and nearly 1450 people
were injured (HRW, 2013). However, Somaliland is considered to be relatively safe in comparison to the Central and Southern Somalia. The main challenges in relation to human security are a high crime level and moral problems. These sociological problems are closely related to education. Due to low levels of education in Somaliland, many illiterate youth become susceptible to the rules and norms of illicit groups. These groups take opportunistic advantage of the widespread poverty in Somaliland and force religiously motivated criminal activities. In addition, there is an increasing number of female discrimination, polygamy, and independent ownership of foreign husbands (misanowane).
